{"id":"1705.06473","submitter":"Andr\\'e K\\\"undgen","authors":"Andr\\'e K\\\"undgen, Janina Patno","title":"Expected reliability of communication protocols","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the problem of sending a message from a sender $s$ to a receiver\n$r$ through an unreliable network by specifying in a protocol what each vertex\nis supposed to do if it receives the message from one of its neighbors. A\nprotocol for routing a message in such a graph is finite if it never floods $r$\nwith an infinite number of copies of the message. The expected reliability of a\ngiven protocol is the probability that a message sent from $s$ reaches $r$ when\nthe edges of the network fail independently with probability $1-p$.\n  We discuss, for given networks, the properties of finite protocols with\nmaximum expected reliability in the case when $p$ is close to 0 or 1, and we\ndescribe networks for which no one protocol is optimal for all values of $p$.\nIn general, finding an optimal protocol for a given network and fixed\nprobability is challenging and many open problems remain.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 18 May 2017 08:49:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-05-19"}
